snippet.textDisplay: So while I appreciate the effort I have some issues with the methodology.  The tires aren't the same at the same time the wheels aren't the same.  The cars aren't the same, is the ride height the same? Brakes, suspension? Too many variables at once guys, you want to test one change at a time.  I'm guessing this also isn't daily driver spec because these are extreme summer tires.  There is some data here but I wouldn't call it useful enough to actually draw conclusions from and it won't help inform people's purchases beyond some vague feelings rather than data from A:B testing.

snippet.textDisplay: Good episode, wish vids like these where out 16 years ago so I would have saved myself the cash & the headaches. Interestingly enough some stock OE rims weigh less than the cheaper aftermarket rims out on the market. If I wanted to save a lb per rim of unsprung mass it would cost about $4-5 grand compared to the stock 19/9 rims on my TT. So there's zero gain for me in that regard. Tires on the other hand make a major difference. A cheap but we'll designed summer sport tire will perform extremely well for the average person on their daily driver. Easier to live with (especially on the budget) for the auto crosser, but not recommended for track days as the tire's compound technology will be apparent almost immediately after the 2nd lap. I look forward to seeing the brake comparison.

snippet.textDisplay: It depends on what you can afford and what you prefer. To tell you the truth.. for me.. I can't justify an extra $2500+ for  0.05 seconds better 400ft slalom run and other minute differences, though the more expensive tires stopped ALOT shorter.. give that cheaper guy another try! If I was a track racer looking for that extra edge and had the cash, then yes, I'd go expensive. But for street driving.. heck no! LOL  I agree the extra spoke pattern looks better though not the extra bolts, but not many people will look at that unless that's one of the things they look for. I go for cheaper.. still better than stock! ;p
